00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:24.450
Trial Mini Symposium four, Focus on ctDNA.

4
00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:28.420
As you'll see this afternoon, we have a collection of a number

5
00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:31.120
of very exciting

6
00:00:32.021 --> 00:00:35.910
and innovative clinical trials that are utilizing

7
00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:39.440
ctDNA in a number of creative ways, both to

8
00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:42.910
understand treatment response, patient selection,

9
00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:47.820
and integration as a predictive biomarkers in a number

10
00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:48.980
of areas.

11
00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:50.180
And

12
00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:55.320
really a great opportunity to understand

13
00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:59.040
and review the technologies being utilized, but more importantly, how we're

14
00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:02.780
applying them into the application of patient care.

15
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.770
So with that, we'll start with our first presenter,

16
00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:12.670
Dr. Yanrong Jiang will be presenting

17
00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:17.340
on neoadjuvant pembrolizumab stratified by tumor mutation burden

18
00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:21.240
and high-risk stage two, three deficient mismatch repair or

19
00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:23.780
MSI-high colorectal cancer. The

20
00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:27.560
NeoPRISM-CRC study. This is looking at

21
00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:30.820
perioperative ultrasensitive ctDNA monitoring and

22
00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.340
tumor-infiltrating TCR repertoire for treatment response

23
00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:36.100
prediction. Dr. Jiang.

24
00:01:42.140 --> 00:01:43.860
Thank you very much for the kind introduction.

25
00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:48.200
On behalf of my collaborators and co-authors, we're very grateful for the

26
00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:52.080
opportunity to present the ctDNA analysis and the T-cell repertoire

27
00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:55.920
analysis, as well as the updated survival outcomes from the NeoPRISM

28
00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:56.820
colorectal trial.

29
00:01:57.940 --> 00:01:58.980
These are my disclosures.

30
00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:04.020
Approximately 15% of colorectal cancers harbor mismatch repair

31
00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.960
deficiency, and these are characterized by high tumor mutation burden as

32
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.780
well as sensitivity to immune checkpoint blockade.

33
00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:14.500
The current standard of care is surgery plus or minus adjuvant

34
00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:18.500
chemotherapy. However, despite this, 20 to

35
00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:21.380
40% of the patients relapse within the first three years.

36
00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:25.620
There's been a number of studies using neoadjuvant immunotherapy in this

37
00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:29.489
space that have shown promising results, both in downstaging the disease and

38
00:02:29.540 --> 00:02:30.840
improving survival outcomes.

39
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:35.480
One of the studies is the NeoPRISM colorectal trial, which

40
00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:39.660
investigated neoadjuvant pembrolizumab in patients with high-risk

41
00:02:39.860 --> 00:02:43.660
stage two or stage three MMRd colorectal cancers in the

42
00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:43.940
UK.

43
00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.780
In total, we enrolled 32 patients, and 31 of whom went on to receive

44
00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:50.800
up to three cycles of pembrolizumab.

45
00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:55.220
All eligible patients proceeded to surgery plus or minus adjuvant

46
00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:55.920
chemotherapy.

47
00:02:56.950 --> 00:03:00.760
The critical questions still remain in this field regarding optimal

48
00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.360
immunotherapy regimen and duration, and we've integrated a

49
00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:08.160
comprehensive translational program in our study to try to address some of these

50
00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:08.740
questions.

51
00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:14.440
First of all, we show that nine weeks of neoadjuvant pembrolizumab achieved

52
00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:18.609
59% pathological complete response in our patients with

53
00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:22.240
no significant safety signals. In addition, more than half of the

54
00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:26.100
patients had high-grade T4 tumors, and a third of the

55
00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:27.329
patients had Lynch syndrome.

56
00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:33.400
Here I'll be presenting the perioperative ctDNA profiling using the Next Personal

57
00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:36.160
assay as well as the T-cell receptor profiling data.

58
00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:41.620
Longitudinal plasma samples were collected at baseline throughout

59
00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:45.390
treatment before each cycle of pembrolizumab preoperatively and

60
00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:49.310
postoperatively. In addition, we collected follow-up samples between

61
00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:53.070
three to 36 months. Baseline tumor biopsies

62
00:03:53.220 --> 00:03:57.160
underwent whole genome sequencing to help design our personalized assay as well as

63
00:03:57.180 --> 00:04:00.860
T-cell receptor profiling. Treatment response was defined by

64
00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.620
histopathological assessment of the resected primary tumor

65
00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:06.260
and the associated lymph nodes.

66
00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:12.340
ctDNA analysis was performed using the Next Personal assay, which

67
00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:16.019
is a whole genome sequencing-based tumor-informed panel

68
00:04:16.221 --> 00:04:19.200
tracking up to 1,400 variants in the samples.

69
00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:23.280
By targeting both coding and non-coding regions, we were able to cover a much

70
00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:25.580
broader range than exome-only techniques.

71
00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:30.140
In addition, background suppression meant that we could go down to median limit of

72
00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:33.820
detection of one to three parts per million using only four milliliters of

73
00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:34.200
plasma.

74
00:04:36.430 --> 00:04:39.960
In total, we analyzed 227 samples in 25

75
00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:43.620
eligible patients, and 97 of these were in the pre-surgery time period.

76
00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:48.410
We detected ctDNA in 100% of the patients at baseline,

77
00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.690
and a quarter of these occurred in the ultrasensitive region of below 100

78
00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:53.160
ppm.

79
00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:57.780
ctDNA detection ranged from one to nearly

80
00:04:57.960 --> 00:04:59.060
60,000 ppm.

81
00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:03.840
This bar chart summarizes the percentage of patients who cleared their

82
00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:05.900
ctDNA throughout the treatment cycles.

83
00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:10.490
At the pre-cycle two time point, 24% of the patients have cleared their

84
00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:11.200
ctDNA.

85
00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:14.960
At the pre-surgery time point after three cycles of treatment,

86
00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:17.380
58% of the patients have cleared.

87
00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.040
And at the post-surgery time point, which was four to five weeks post-surgery, all

88
00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:23.980
of the patients had cleared their ctDNA.

89
00:05:26.210 --> 00:05:29.820
We then looked at the ctDNA kinetic profiles in our cohort, and the

90
00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:33.840
ctDNA clearance is represented by the logarithmic scale on the y-axis

91
00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:36.960
in these plots, and three distinct patterns emerged.

92
00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:42.580
First, there was a group of patients who rapidly and completely

93
00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.880
cleared their ctDNA after one cycle of treatment, and this

94
00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:50.660
group of super molecular responders all achieved pathological complete response.

95
00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.120
Secondly, there was a group of dynamic molecular responders who had rapid

96
00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.940
reduction of ctDNA levels to less than 100

97
00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:03.540
ppm pre-surgery, and 80% of these patients achieved

98
00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:07.600
PCRAnd finally, there was a group of patients who had

99
00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:11.560
stable or rising ctDNA levels, and in this group of poor molecular

100
00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:14.940
responders, none of the patients cleared their ctDNA.

101
00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:19.260
Importantly, ctDNA kinetics in our study was irrespective of

102
00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:23.260
patients' radiological stage, histology, age, sex,

103
00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:26.680
Lynch syndrome status, or other standard clinical parameters.

104
00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:31.760
We then asked how this could be applied to real-time clinical practice

105
00:06:31.880 --> 00:06:35.600
decision-making, and we propose that in the super molecular responders,

106
00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:38.659
these patients could be considered for non-operative management.

107
00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:43.040
The dynamic molecular responders could be considered for continuing

108
00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:46.960
immunotherapy and/or operate. And the poor

109
00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:50.880
molecular responders, we recommend operating or considering treatment

110
00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:52.340
intensification in this group.

111
00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:58.169
We also assess ctDNA as a post-operative

112
00:06:58.320 --> 00:06:59.620
surveillance MRD tool.

113
00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:04.420
And currently, we have a median follow-up of nearly 33 months, and no

114
00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:08.160
patients have relapsed so far. Two of our patients have had CAPOX

115
00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:12.040
adjuvant chemotherapy, but without prior knowledge of their ctDNA status.

116
00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:12.970
And

117
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.860
this swimmer plot shows the plasma samples that we have processed

118
00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:20.260
up to 24 months of follow-up in these patients.

119
00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:24.840
And as we can see, the ctDNA surveillance demonstrated 100%

120
00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:28.440
specificity with no false positives in the study and

121
00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:32.000
100% negative prediction value. And so in our study,

122
00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:36.000
undetectable post-operative ctDNA accurately predicted

123
00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:37.120
relapse-free status.

124
00:07:39.310 --> 00:07:42.880
We then asked whether we could find any biomarkers that could predict patients'

125
00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:45.320
response before they start immunotherapy treatment.

126
00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:50.180
In other tumor types, T cell receptor sequencing metrics have been

127
00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:55.700
assessed as a biomarker. In particular, large T cell clonal

128
00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:59.340
expansion is associated with high immunogenicity and a

129
00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:01.240
favorable response to immunotherapy.

130
00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:05.620
And therefore, we performed RNA-based targeted TCR

131
00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:09.500
profiling of our baseline tumor biopsies on 31

132
00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:13.380
eligible baseline tumors using a technique called Fume TCR-Seq.

133
00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:19.280
In particular, we focused on a group of expanded large clones and compared these

134
00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:23.080
across the treatment groups. And as we can see from the violin plot, the

135
00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:27.080
patients who went on to achieve complete pathological response had

136
00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:29.540
more expanded large clones than those who did not.

137
00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:35.270
And this suggests that responders harbored pre-existing

138
00:08:35.300 --> 00:08:38.860
poised anti-tumor T cells, which is unleashed by pembrolizumab's

139
00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:43.201
mechanism of action. And this also provides a mechanistic explanation for

140
00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:46.500
the rapid ctDNA reduction in our molecular responders.

141
00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:52.400
We then asked what the potential predictive performance might be to

142
00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:56.360
integrate these two approaches, and this is shown by the Bayesian model on

143
00:08:56.380 --> 00:08:57.380
the left of the slide.

144
00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:02.200
On the x-axis is the TCR clonal expansion, and on the y-axis

145
00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:03.840
is the ctDNA reduction.

146
00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:08.340
Each individual dot represents a patient in our cohort, and the

147
00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:11.960
contours represent the probability of achieving complete pathological

148
00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:15.780
response. And as we can see, patients who had strong TCR clonal

149
00:09:15.790 --> 00:09:19.120
expansion and who cleared their ctDNA rapidly

150
00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:22.560
clustered in the region of high probability of

151
00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:26.520
achieving a response. And patients who had low TCR

152
00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:30.410
clonal expansion and who cleared their ctDNA slowly clustered in

153
00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:32.860
this region of low probability of response.

154
00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:38.300
And so dynamic ctDNA clearance adds a strong discrimination layer beyond

155
00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:42.160
TCR alone, separating patients with similar immune profiles

156
00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:45.190
into distinct confidence regions of achieving response.

157
00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:49.340
And we propose that this could possibly be used as a tool for real-time clinical

158
00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:50.780
decision making in the future.

159
00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.120
In summary, here are the key translational findings from our study.

160
00:09:57.120 --> 00:10:00.660
First of all, ctDNA was detected in 100% of our

161
00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:04.440
patients, with 24% of these detections in the ultrasensitive

162
00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:06.160
range of less than 100 ppm.

163
00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:10.520
In addition, ctDNA had 100% longitudinal

164
00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:14.280
post-operative specificity and negative prediction value for relapse.

165
00:10:15.580 --> 00:10:19.080
100% of the super molecular responders achieved complete

166
00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:22.640
pathological response, while poor molecular responders did not.

167
00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:28.460
In terms of the immune profiling, tumor T cell receptor clonality may predict

168
00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:32.220
patients who will have an excellent response prior to their first

169
00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:33.680
cycle of immunotherapy.

170
00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:38.500
In addition, a combined model incorporating both TCR and ctDNA

171
00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:40.820
clearance predicts individual patient response.

172
00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:47.200
Here are the key clinical implications

173
00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:51.080
from our trial. Nine weeks of pre-operative single agent pembrolizumab

174
00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:55.080
in DMMR high risk stage two or stage three colorectal cancers

175
00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:58.800
results in significant disease downstaging with 59%

176
00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:02.490
PCR. There were no new adverse safety signals, and

177
00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:06.700
with a median follow-up of nearly 33 months, there was no disease relapse.

178
00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:11.320
These are the points that are potentially practice changing.

179
00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:15.660
Early ctDNA clearance may allow for selection of super responders to single

180
00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.600
agent immunotherapy for non-operative management.

181
00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:23.220
In addition, post-operative ctDNA clearance allows for selective requirement

182
00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:24.560
of adjuvant therapies.

183
00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:29.500
Baseline TCR profiling has the potential to predict patient response

184
00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:33.020
even before beginning the first cycle of immunotherapy treatment.

185
00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:37.500
And finally, we propose that early adoption of these approaches into future

186
00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:40.619
prospective, adaptive, biomarker-informed clinical trials.

187
00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:44.650
Thank you. And first of all, we'd like to thank all our patients and their families

188
00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:46.140
for contributing to the clinical trial.

189
00:11:46.850 --> 00:11:50.670
We'd like to thank all our clinical colleagues from across the UK, as well as our

190
00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:54.180
scientific collaborators, in particular Personalis.

191
00:11:54.760 --> 00:11:58.630
And finally, we'd like to thank MSD for funding the trial and UCL for sponsoring

192
00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:00.120
the trial. Thank you very much.

