Thank you very much for the question.

252
00:15:22.484 --> 00:15:26.054
That's one of the great things about having the whole genome sequencing data as

253
00:15:26.084 --> 00:15:29.564
well, that these are some of the further things that we would definitely like to

254
00:15:29.604 --> 00:15:33.024
look into in the future, again, as exploratory biomarkers of

255
00:15:33.044 --> 00:15:33.844
response.

256
00:15:33.874 --> 00:15:34.144
Bria.

257
00:15:39.784 --> 00:15:41.704
Okay. Thank you very much, Dr. Jiang.

258
00:15:41.824 --> 00:15:42.424
Thank you very much.

259
00:15:45.004 --> 00:15:48.744
I'll turn it over to my co-chair to introduce himself and our next speaker.

260
00:15:49.664 --> 00:15:52.984
Thank you very much. Yeah, that was so excellent.

261
00:15:53.124 --> 00:15:55.384
Now we're going to move on. So I'm Adil Chaudhry.

262
00:15:55.404 --> 00:15:58.884
I'm a physician scientist at the Mayo Clinic, and my lab focuses on

263
00:15:58.944 --> 00:16:01.024
ctDNA liquid biopsy technologies.

264
00:16:02.284 --> 00:16:05.944
Brings me great pleasure to introduce our next speaker, Julia

265
00:16:05.964 --> 00:16:09.134
Foldy, and she'll be presenting on early findings from

266
00:16:09.144 --> 00:16:13.044
MONITOR-BREAST, ctDNA dynamics during neoadjuvant therapy

267
00:16:13.104 --> 00:16:16.964
using an ultrasensitive MRD assay. Julia, the floor is yours.

268
00:16:21.404 --> 00:16:23.624
Thank you very much for that introduction.

269
00:16:23.644 --> 00:16:27.524
On behalf of my co-investigators, I'm delighted to present here

270
00:16:27.584 --> 00:16:30.064
early findings from the MONITOR-BREAST study.

271
00:16:31.544 --> 00:16:35.444
Here are my disclosures. I have no financial relationships with Myriad

272
00:16:35.484 --> 00:16:36.844
Genetics to disclose.

273
00:16:38.984 --> 00:16:42.544
So in breast oncology, pathologic response to

274
00:16:42.604 --> 00:16:46.324
neoadjuvant therapy has been used as a risk stratification tool,

275
00:16:46.444 --> 00:16:50.264
particularly in those patients with HER2 positive and triple negative

276
00:16:50.284 --> 00:16:51.184
breast cancers.

277
00:16:52.564 --> 00:16:56.424
As seen here in a representative Kaplan-Meier

278
00:16:56.544 --> 00:16:58.504
plot from the I-SPY 2 study,

279
00:16:59.964 --> 00:17:03.564
increasing residual cancer burden, or RCB index, which is a

280
00:17:03.624 --> 00:17:07.404
marker of poor tumor response to neoadjuvant therapy, is

281
00:17:07.464 --> 00:17:11.264
associated with worse distant relapse-free survival

282
00:17:11.545 --> 00:17:13.844
in patients with early stage breast cancers.

283
00:17:15.224 --> 00:17:18.384
More recently, ctDNA positivity, both at

284
00:17:18.424 --> 00:17:22.204
diagnosis and post neoadjuvant therapy, have been shown to

285
00:17:22.244 --> 00:17:25.585
be independent predictors of metastatic recurrence,

286
00:17:26.144 --> 00:17:29.604
as well as ctDNA clearance and negativity

287
00:17:30.224 --> 00:17:33.744
being associated with favorable long-term outcomes in

288
00:17:33.804 --> 00:17:37.684
multiple different studies using different MRD assays.

289
00:17:39.804 --> 00:17:43.424
The plot from the I-SPY 2 study shows that for the

290
00:17:43.484 --> 00:17:47.164
same RCB index, patients with negative ctDNA after

291
00:17:47.244 --> 00:17:50.944
neoadjuvant therapy have significantly improved long-term outcomes

292
00:17:51.004 --> 00:17:54.844
compared to patients with the same RCB index, but positive ctDNA.

293
00:17:55.864 --> 00:17:59.724
Importantly, in patients who do not achieve a PCR but

294
00:17:59.764 --> 00:18:03.644
have negative ctDNA after neoadjuvant therapy, shown both in the

295
00:18:03.664 --> 00:18:07.184
PredictDNA and NSABP B-59

296
00:18:07.304 --> 00:18:11.084
studies, these patients have nearly as good long-term outcomes as

297
00:18:11.124 --> 00:18:13.884
patients who achieve a path CR after neoadjuvant

298
00:18:13.904 --> 00:18:17.884
therapy.A lot of these earlier studies have

299
00:18:17.964 --> 00:18:21.844
used less sensitive MRD assays

300
00:18:21.864 --> 00:18:25.364
and sparse sampling that may have missed critical time points.

301
00:18:27.364 --> 00:18:31.164
Therefore, the aim of the MONITOR-Breast study's neoadjuvant cohort

302
00:18:31.364 --> 00:18:35.004
was to prospectively evaluate the association between ctDNA

303
00:18:35.064 --> 00:18:38.524
dynamics and pathologic response across breast cancer

304
00:18:38.544 --> 00:18:39.284
subtypes.

305
00:18:40.364 --> 00:18:43.764
The population of this study included patients with all breast cancer

306
00:18:43.864 --> 00:18:47.344
subtypes, early stages one, two, and three, receiving

307
00:18:47.384 --> 00:18:49.044
real-world treatment regimens.

308
00:18:50.024 --> 00:18:53.884
We used an ultrasensitive whole-genome sequencing-based assay that

309
00:18:53.944 --> 00:18:57.304
tracked up to 1,000 individualized variants per patient,

310
00:18:57.784 --> 00:19:01.724
detecting ctDNA down to levels under 100

311
00:19:01.804 --> 00:19:02.423
ppm.

312
00:19:03.324 --> 00:19:07.184
We also used dense sampling in this study, including a

313
00:19:07.224 --> 00:19:10.324
diagnosis at each cycle of neoadjuvant

314
00:19:10.404 --> 00:19:14.334
therapy, the post-neoadjuvant therapy time point, surgery,

315
00:19:14.724 --> 00:19:16.104
and the post-op time point.

316
00:19:18.194 --> 00:19:21.014
This consort diagram here shows our enrollment.

317
00:19:21.484 --> 00:19:25.124
A total of 424 patients were enrolled.

318
00:19:25.144 --> 00:19:28.824
A subset of them are in a separate adjuvant cohort who are

319
00:19:28.864 --> 00:19:32.824
currently being followed. In this particular neoadjuvant

320
00:19:32.964 --> 00:19:35.864
study, 132 patients were enrolled.

321
00:19:36.284 --> 00:19:39.864
120 of them had successful panel creation,

322
00:19:39.944 --> 00:19:43.804
representing a 91% success rate. And here I'm

323
00:19:43.824 --> 00:19:47.324
presenting data on 113 patients who had at least

324
00:19:47.404 --> 00:19:50.064
three plasma samples available for analysis.

325
00:19:51.024 --> 00:19:54.584
All of these patients were female with a median age of 56 years,

326
00:19:55.024 --> 00:19:58.624
representing all subtypes and early stages of breast cancer.

327
00:19:58.984 --> 00:20:02.904
Most had ductal cancers and single primary tumors,

328
00:20:03.384 --> 00:20:06.744
and just over half of them had node-negative disease.

329
00:20:06.804 --> 00:20:10.584
A total of 844 plasma samples were analyzed for a

330
00:20:10.624 --> 00:20:12.884
median of nine time points per patient.

331
00:20:13.924 --> 00:20:16.684
In terms of treatment, all patients received chemotherapy,

332
00:20:17.264 --> 00:20:20.664
42% received immunotherapy, and 36% received

333
00:20:20.724 --> 00:20:22.044
HER2-targeted therapy.

334
00:20:23.024 --> 00:20:26.273
This pie chart here shows the distribution of receptor subtypes.

335
00:20:26.944 --> 00:20:30.924
40% of patients had triple-negative, and 36%

336
00:20:30.964 --> 00:20:34.024
had HER2-positive breast cancers, while the remaining

337
00:20:34.224 --> 00:20:38.024
25% had hormone receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancers.

338
00:20:38.904 --> 00:20:42.804
The stage distribution shown here reveals that

339
00:20:42.884 --> 00:20:46.794
most patients had stage two cancers, while there was an enrichment

340
00:20:46.844 --> 00:20:50.604
of stage three cancers in the hormone receptor-positive, HER2-negative

341
00:20:50.644 --> 00:20:51.144
subgroup.

342
00:20:53.964 --> 00:20:57.204
This slide shows baseline ctDNA detection rates.

343
00:20:57.404 --> 00:21:01.244
In all patients, 91% had detectable

344
00:21:01.404 --> 00:21:05.234
ctDNA at baseline, which increased with disease burden by

345
00:21:05.404 --> 00:21:09.284
stage, clinical T stage, and nodal status.

346
00:21:10.324 --> 00:21:13.654
When broken down by breast cancer subtype, we can see that

347
00:21:13.824 --> 00:21:17.524
100% of those patients with hormone receptor-positive, HER2-negative

348
00:21:17.564 --> 00:21:21.064
disease had detectable ctDNA at baseline, and the highest

349
00:21:22.444 --> 00:21:26.244
median tumor fraction was detected in those with triple-negative breast cancers.

350
00:21:27.364 --> 00:21:31.344
Importantly, 20% of all samples were detected in the ultrasensitive

351
00:21:31.484 --> 00:21:33.504
range under 100 ppm.

352
00:21:35.364 --> 00:21:38.944
Now to look at ctDNA dynamics and pathologic response.

353
00:21:39.584 --> 00:21:42.964
This spider plot here shows four different time points:

354
00:21:43.464 --> 00:21:47.364
baseline, the last neoadjuvant therapy time

355
00:21:47.424 --> 00:21:51.024
point available for each patient, the post-neoadjuvant time point, and the

356
00:21:51.124 --> 00:21:54.964
post-op time point. And you can see these different patterns

357
00:21:55.004 --> 00:21:58.374
between patients who had residual disease versus those with PCR.

358
00:21:59.104 --> 00:22:02.984
A different way of looking at this is the proportion of patients

359
00:22:03.044 --> 00:22:06.484
who had ctDNA positivity in orange or

360
00:22:06.524 --> 00:22:10.464
ctDNA negative assays in blue at

361
00:22:10.484 --> 00:22:14.064
these four different time points based on whether they had residual disease

362
00:22:14.224 --> 00:22:15.364
versus a past CR.

363
00:22:16.264 --> 00:22:19.904
The takeaway from this data is that all 47 patients who

364
00:22:19.964 --> 00:22:23.624
achieved PCR had ctDNA negative status at the

365
00:22:23.644 --> 00:22:26.024
post-neoadjuvant time point for 100%

366
00:22:26.104 --> 00:22:30.084
specificity. Conversely, 32% of patients

367
00:22:30.124 --> 00:22:34.023
who had residual disease were ctDNA positive at the post-neoadjuvant

368
00:22:34.124 --> 00:22:38.004
time point. This is in contrast to earlier studies with

369
00:22:38.044 --> 00:22:41.624
less sensitive assays, which showed this to be in the range of 14% to

370
00:22:41.704 --> 00:22:42.604
20%.

371
00:22:44.504 --> 00:22:48.444
Overall, 67% of samples were in the ultrasensitive range.

372
00:22:49.144 --> 00:22:52.924
And in patients who had a post-neoadjuvant therapy time point where they were

373
00:22:52.984 --> 00:22:56.424
ctDNA positive had a 43 times higher

374
00:22:56.484 --> 00:22:59.944
chance of being ctDNA positive after surgery.

375
00:23:03.524 --> 00:23:07.324
CtDNA dynamics yielded distinct patterns based on

376
00:23:07.344 --> 00:23:08.524
breast cancer subtype.

377
00:23:09.504 --> 00:23:13.144
This shows here that patients who had hormone receptor-positive,

378
00:23:13.224 --> 00:23:16.704
HER2-negative disease shown in orange, cleared their

379
00:23:16.764 --> 00:23:20.304
ctDNA later than patients with triple-negative and HER2

380
00:23:20.364 --> 00:23:21.384
positive disease.

381
00:23:23.484 --> 00:23:24.754
Triple negative patients,

382
00:23:25.624 --> 00:23:28.924
within 45 days, 90% of them cleared their

383
00:23:28.944 --> 00:23:32.864
ctDNA, whereas in hormone receptor-positive subset,

384
00:23:33.194 --> 00:23:36.824
these patients required 16 weeks to capture 90% of

385
00:23:36.864 --> 00:23:40.694
clearances. The timing of clearance alone, however, did not

386
00:23:40.724 --> 00:23:44.184
predict PCR, but sustained negativity did.

387
00:23:45.064 --> 00:23:48.324
So we observed three different patterns of clearance.

388
00:23:48.664 --> 00:23:52.144
The first one was sustained MRD negativity,

389
00:23:52.224 --> 00:23:54.924
representing 76% of all patients.

390
00:23:55.724 --> 00:23:59.524
The remaining were split equally between those who were persistently

391
00:23:59.644 --> 00:24:03.044
MRD positive versus those who had intermittent MRD

392
00:24:03.084 --> 00:24:06.904
positivity. And you can see here the PCR rates for each

393
00:24:06.984 --> 00:24:10.664
group being 63% for those with sustained

394
00:24:10.824 --> 00:24:14.204
MRD negative assays versus

395
00:24:14.484 --> 00:24:18.184
0% and 7% for the persistently MRD positive and

396
00:24:18.264 --> 00:24:20.264
intermittently positive population,

397
00:24:20.324 --> 00:24:24.084
respectively.To dive deeper into these three

398
00:24:24.164 --> 00:24:25.404
separate patterns.

399
00:24:26.784 --> 00:24:30.444
This shows those patients who had sustained

400
00:24:30.484 --> 00:24:34.404
ctDNA clearance. You can see here that the timing was quite

401
00:24:34.484 --> 00:24:37.104
different for individual patients.

402
00:24:38.104 --> 00:24:42.004
But what was important is that these patients continued neoadjuvant

403
00:24:42.044 --> 00:24:45.284
therapy for an average of 119 days after

404
00:24:45.424 --> 00:24:48.584
clearance with undetectable ctDNA.

405
00:24:49.504 --> 00:24:53.424
A subset of these patients also had RCB data available, and

406
00:24:53.464 --> 00:24:57.024
we can see here that very few patients had RCB3

407
00:24:57.064 --> 00:24:58.684
residual disease in this group.

408
00:24:59.724 --> 00:25:03.584
Post-op ctDNA was available for a subset of patients, as

409
00:25:03.644 --> 00:25:07.144
this is an ongoing study, and two out of 69

410
00:25:07.204 --> 00:25:09.934
patients had a post-op positive ctDNA.

411
00:25:10.964 --> 00:25:14.824
Importantly, 63% of sustained clearers achieved a

412
00:25:14.864 --> 00:25:18.604
PCR versus 4% in those patients in the

413
00:25:18.684 --> 00:25:20.624
persistent and intermittent groups.

414
00:25:21.704 --> 00:25:25.344
To look at these two groups in more detail, in red here are the

415
00:25:25.384 --> 00:25:29.244
patients who had persistently positive ctDNA, while

416
00:25:29.284 --> 00:25:33.084
in orange are those who had intermittent ctDNA positivity.

417
00:25:34.064 --> 00:25:37.504
100% of patients in the persistently positive

418
00:25:37.604 --> 00:25:40.984
group had residual disease and all had RCB2 or

419
00:25:41.064 --> 00:25:43.304
3 category residual disease.

420
00:25:44.544 --> 00:25:48.194
Of the nine patients who had a post-op time point assay available,

421
00:25:48.364 --> 00:25:52.094
six of them remained ctDNA positive at the first post-operative

422
00:25:52.144 --> 00:25:52.554
visit.

423
00:25:53.584 --> 00:25:56.924
Of the patients who had intermittently positive MRD assays,

424
00:25:57.584 --> 00:26:00.944
93% had residual disease at surgery.

425
00:26:00.964 --> 00:26:04.844
And interestingly, when MRD positivity re-emerged in these

426
00:26:04.924 --> 00:26:08.424
patients, often it was seen under 20

427
00:26:08.484 --> 00:26:12.464
ppm, and so this is only visible with really sensitive

428
00:26:12.504 --> 00:26:13.804
assays and frequent

429
00:26:14.704 --> 00:26:15.524
time points.

430
00:26:16.484 --> 00:26:20.244
So additional sampling identifies more patients who are at risk for

431
00:26:20.284 --> 00:26:21.304
residual disease.

432
00:26:23.344 --> 00:26:27.164
In summary, frequent ultrasensitive MRD testing

433
00:26:27.264 --> 00:26:30.923
reveals response patterns not visible with sparse sampling.

434
00:26:31.664 --> 00:26:35.344
We see different patterns and opportunities for treatment

435
00:26:35.404 --> 00:26:39.324
optimization. The majority of patients who had

436
00:26:39.384 --> 00:26:43.174
sustained MRD clearance, and often early during neoadjuvant therapy,

437
00:26:43.864 --> 00:26:46.724
may have opportunities for therapy de-escalation.

438
00:26:47.384 --> 00:26:50.964
Conversely, the patients who had persistent or intermittent MRD

439
00:26:51.024 --> 00:26:51.754
positivity,

440
00:26:52.984 --> 00:26:56.204
most of them had residual disease, and this might be a

441
00:26:56.244 --> 00:26:59.524
population where we can think about escalation of treatment.

442
00:27:00.984 --> 00:27:04.944
Importantly, frequent testing identified 64% more patients

443
00:27:04.984 --> 00:27:08.884
who were at risk for residual disease versus testing only at the

444
00:27:08.924 --> 00:27:12.084
post-neoadjuvant time point. Post-neoadjuvant

445
00:27:12.184 --> 00:27:15.664
ctDNA was significantly associated with pathologic

446
00:27:15.744 --> 00:27:18.324
response as well as post-operative ctDNA.

447
00:27:19.484 --> 00:27:22.944
Long-term survival outcomes are not yet available as study follow-up is

448
00:27:23.024 --> 00:27:23.504
ongoing.

449
00:27:24.704 --> 00:27:28.644
And future MRD-guided prospective trials should determine whether acting on these

450
00:27:28.684 --> 00:27:32.444
response patterns have utility to meaningfully change outcomes

451
00:27:32.584 --> 00:27:34.284
beyond our standard approaches.

452
00:27:36.124 --> 00:27:39.844
And with that, I would like to thank everyone for their attention and thank

453
00:27:40.064 --> 00:27:44.044
all of the patients who participated in our study, their families and clinicians

454
00:27:44.064 --> 00:27:47.574
for their support, and all of the sites across the United States

455
00:27:47.584 --> 00:27:51.544
and in Japan who participated in this study. Thank you very much.

456
00:27:58.424 --> 00:28:01.364
Thank you very much, Julia. That was truly excellent.

457
00:28:01.484 --> 00:28:03.224
Any questions from the audience?

458
00:28:05.044 --> 00:28:08.764
Maybe I'll start with one. So I think you

459
00:28:08.784 --> 00:28:12.534
really demonstrated the power of both ultrasensitive detection

460
00:28:12.604 --> 00:28:16.244
technologies and also the importance of serial sampling.

461
00:28:16.344 --> 00:28:18.713
But kind of one thing that struck me is that

462
00:28:20.464 --> 00:28:24.304
many of these patients who have

463
00:28:24.364 --> 00:28:28.224
residual disease detectable remain negative even with

464
00:28:28.364 --> 00:28:30.984
ultrasensitive testing and even with serial testing.

465
00:28:31.064 --> 00:28:31.184
So

466
00:28:32.784 --> 00:28:36.644
is there something beyond even ppm

467
00:28:36.684 --> 00:28:39.114
detection limits in order to capture these patients?

468
00:28:39.184 --> 00:28:42.744
And how close are we truly to being able to

469
00:28:42.764 --> 00:28:45.264
de-escalate based off of ctDNA MRD?

470
00:28:46.664 --> 00:28:48.124
Yeah. So that's an excellent question.

471
00:28:48.224 --> 00:28:50.884
I think we know that

472
00:28:52.024 --> 00:28:54.983
MRD positivity has a clear

473
00:28:56.184 --> 00:28:59.864
predictable consequence, but we don't always know what a negative test

474
00:28:59.924 --> 00:29:01.524
means. And

475
00:29:02.344 --> 00:29:05.664
we're seeing this with these ultrasensitive assays from multiple

476
00:29:05.804 --> 00:29:09.304
studies, so perhaps it's not the sensitivity

477
00:29:10.104 --> 00:29:13.404
that really matters. We don't really know

478
00:29:15.184 --> 00:29:18.644
whether it's going to be the pathologic response

479
00:29:19.024 --> 00:29:19.324
or

480
00:29:20.164 --> 00:29:23.964
the ctDNA that's going to tell us more information, although we're starting to get

481
00:29:23.984 --> 00:29:27.904
more and more information about that, seeing from multiple studies

482
00:29:27.924 --> 00:29:31.784
now that even in patients who have residual disease, if they're MRD

483
00:29:31.794 --> 00:29:35.544
negative at the end of neoadjuvant therapy, they have excellent

484
00:29:35.604 --> 00:29:39.024
long-term outcomes, and then perhaps that's what is going to determine

485
00:29:39.184 --> 00:29:41.804
our next steps in treatment.

486
00:29:43.184 --> 00:29:43.644
Thank you.

487
00:29:47.364 --> 00:29:48.384
I can ask one more.

488
00:29:49.484 --> 00:29:49.904
So you

489
00:29:51.084 --> 00:29:54.944
demonstrated, as mentioned, really the value of the dense sampling

490
00:29:55.004 --> 00:29:56.784
in the context of this clinical trial.

491
00:29:57.524 --> 00:30:01.244
As the field moves forward to larger studies,

492
00:30:03.344 --> 00:30:07.004
is there a single time point or time points that you would recommend

493
00:30:07.064 --> 00:30:09.624
that future studies should utilize?

494
00:30:11.664 --> 00:30:12.124
So I think

495
00:30:13.004 --> 00:30:16.144
what this study really illustrates, like you mentioned, is that

496
00:30:17.284 --> 00:30:19.684
more time points provide more information.

497
00:30:20.444 --> 00:30:24.374
And one thing that we all have to think about is whether this is feasible to

498
00:30:24.424 --> 00:30:28.316
do in routine practice, right? Is it feasible toTo

499
00:30:28.326 --> 00:30:29.856
assay at every single

500
00:30:30.876 --> 00:30:34.856
cycle. And the answer is probably not going to be

501
00:30:34.916 --> 00:30:36.096
feasible.

502
00:30:36.976 --> 00:30:40.826
But we did see in this study that the single post-neoadjuvent time point is

503
00:30:40.836 --> 00:30:44.476
probably not enough to give us all of the information needed.

504
00:30:44.636 --> 00:30:48.616
I think we don't have the data to say which time

505
00:30:48.656 --> 00:30:50.096
point is most important.

506
00:30:51.236 --> 00:30:54.516
And we saw that even in patients who cleared early but then

507
00:30:54.596 --> 00:30:58.506
re-emerged at ultra-sensitive levels, that

508
00:30:58.656 --> 00:31:01.396
all by itself predicted residual disease.

509
00:31:01.816 --> 00:31:05.756
So I can't answer that question because we don't have the data, but I think

510
00:31:05.816 --> 00:31:06.056
that

511
00:31:06.876 --> 00:31:10.756
doing these frequent assays is going to be important as much

512
00:31:10.796 --> 00:31:11.616
as it's feasible.

513
00:31:14.196 --> 00:31:14.556
Please.

514
00:31:14.816 --> 00:31:18.536
Maria Belic from Pittsburgh. A very nice presentation, Julia.

