00:54:00.940 --> 00:54:04.780
and the patient remains disease-free almost two years from the end of the therapy.

894
00:54:05.700 --> 00:54:09.420
Similar kinetics were observed on the patients who

895
00:54:10.060 --> 00:54:12.220
were observed in HPV DNA

896
00:54:13.220 --> 00:54:13.800
analysis.

897
00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:20.280
This is a swimmer plot that tries to show how was the distribution of the

898
00:54:20.300 --> 00:54:23.300
ctDNA analysis in all the patients of the study who were evaluable.

899
00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:27.840
Beyond patient 13, patient 15 have positive

900
00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:31.680
detection of ctDNA across all the time points with increasing rates

901
00:54:32.140 --> 00:54:36.020
and later progression 190 days from the end of

902
00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:36.780
the part B.

903
00:54:37.880 --> 00:54:41.460
Similarly, patient 19, who was not eligible because of

904
00:54:41.480 --> 00:54:45.060
PD-L1 negativity, had a similar situation with progression

905
00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:46.420
235 days.

906
00:54:47.560 --> 00:54:51.100
There is one patient, 31, who was negative at part B

907
00:54:51.480 --> 00:54:55.240
but later was positive during part E and had progression 76

908
00:54:55.300 --> 00:54:58.990
days later. So in these three cases, some lead time from the

909
00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:02.848
detection of ctDNA.Patient 3, 25, and

910
00:55:02.968 --> 00:55:06.248
36 had both ctDNA and

911
00:55:06.748 --> 00:55:08.908
radiological progression at the end of part B.

912
00:55:10.848 --> 00:55:14.408
In contrast, we have a patient, patient eight, who was

913
00:55:14.588 --> 00:55:18.528
negative during part B and had radiological progression at

914
00:55:18.588 --> 00:55:20.968
the end of part B, being a false negative.

915
00:55:21.668 --> 00:55:25.628
Patient 21 and 42 are patients where ctDNA was

916
00:55:25.688 --> 00:55:29.548
not detected during the surveillance and have later progression with a

917
00:55:29.608 --> 00:55:30.988
lead time from the end of part B.

918
00:55:32.228 --> 00:55:35.788
Patient 12 was a patient who had ctDNA

919
00:55:35.828 --> 00:55:39.437
detection four to six weeks after the end of definitive therapy,

920
00:55:39.788 --> 00:55:42.788
but later clear ctDNA with progression two years later.

921
00:55:44.068 --> 00:55:47.768
The only case that was positive during surveillance, it was

922
00:55:47.868 --> 00:55:51.748
patient 40, and the only case that

923
00:55:52.108 --> 00:55:56.028
had a positive result during surveillance and didn't have

924
00:55:56.068 --> 00:55:59.508
radiological progression is patient 40, where there was ctDNA

925
00:55:59.548 --> 00:56:00.768
detection during part E.

926
00:56:01.588 --> 00:56:05.528
However, the follow-up of this patient is still below a year, so we need

927
00:56:05.608 --> 00:56:08.728
further time to see whether this was a false positive or not.

928
00:56:09.908 --> 00:56:12.328
Of note, all the PD samples

929
00:56:13.308 --> 00:56:16.808
that were collected at the time of progression were positive for ctDNA.

930
00:56:19.228 --> 00:56:23.048
We also analyzed whether detection of ctDNA in any of these

931
00:56:23.068 --> 00:56:26.828
time points or in all the time points of surveillance were

932
00:56:26.868 --> 00:56:30.148
associated with recurrence. As you can see here, there is a

933
00:56:30.188 --> 00:56:30.868
clear

934
00:56:31.688 --> 00:56:35.628
correlation between detection of ctDNA and worse outcomes with

935
00:56:35.648 --> 00:56:38.728
a sensitivity of only 50% at the end of part B,

936
00:56:39.268 --> 00:56:42.368
but including longitudinal tracking going up to

937
00:56:42.548 --> 00:56:46.288
73% with a very good specificity at all the time points.

938
00:56:48.028 --> 00:56:51.808
We finally explore whether hpDNA detection in the

939
00:56:51.908 --> 00:56:55.528
subset of patients with oropharyngeal cancer HPV-driven was

940
00:56:55.568 --> 00:56:58.728
associated with worse outcomes. And similar to what we saw

941
00:57:00.348 --> 00:57:04.068
with the RADAR assay, we observed that ctDNA

942
00:57:04.088 --> 00:57:06.948
detection was associated with worse outcomes.

943
00:57:07.628 --> 00:57:11.618
Of note, for both analyses, RADAR and HPV, we excluded patient

944
00:57:11.728 --> 00:57:14.188
17 as this patient had received interception.

945
00:57:14.528 --> 00:57:18.248
But nevertheless, you can see a good sensitivity with a lower specificity

946
00:57:18.528 --> 00:57:20.388
due to a higher number of false positive.

947
00:57:22.348 --> 00:57:26.138
So in conclusion, MERIDIAN is, to our knowledge, the first MRD interception

948
00:57:26.188 --> 00:57:29.568
study in patients with locally advanced head and neck squamous cell carcinoma

949
00:57:29.588 --> 00:57:30.468
post-definitive therapy.

950
00:57:31.488 --> 00:57:35.208
Despite the study was closed, was paused earlier due to a lower than expected

951
00:57:35.328 --> 00:57:39.208
MRD prevalence, the single patient who was randomized to rebirotinib

952
00:57:39.268 --> 00:57:43.168
achieved a ctDNA clearance which is persistent and is currently free of disease

953
00:57:43.248 --> 00:57:44.008
two years later.

954
00:57:45.208 --> 00:57:49.168
Post-treatment ctDNA using RADAR was associated with recurrence, with three cases

955
00:57:49.228 --> 00:57:51.628
having some significant lead time prior to progression.

956
00:57:52.208 --> 00:57:56.008
And despite MRD sensitivity at the follow-up two-time point,

957
00:57:56.048 --> 00:57:59.968
with those eight to 12 weeks after therapy was only 50%, that

958
00:58:00.008 --> 00:58:01.448
improved with serial monitoring.

959
00:58:02.648 --> 00:58:05.968
hpDNA offered higher sensitivity but lower specificity than

960
00:58:05.988 --> 00:58:08.068
RADAR in OPC patients.

961
00:58:09.308 --> 00:58:12.568
Based on these learnings, we have amended the protocol and we have reopened the

962
00:58:12.628 --> 00:58:16.508
protocol using a potentially more sensitive assay with a lower level of

963
00:58:16.568 --> 00:58:18.768
detection, which is the Personal Nex.

964
00:58:19.328 --> 00:58:23.128
We have also included longitudinal tracking similar to IMvigor011,

965
00:58:23.908 --> 00:58:26.868
one time point every three months for the first year, and we have removed

966
00:58:27.948 --> 00:58:31.448
randomization to try to allow more patients to benefit from interception

967
00:58:31.488 --> 00:58:32.168
opportunities.

968
00:58:33.568 --> 00:58:37.248
I would like to thank finally all the study team, especially Dr.

969
00:58:37.268 --> 00:58:41.248
Lilian Siu and Dr. Scott Brahmer for their co-leadership on this trial,

970
00:58:41.848 --> 00:58:45.568
the Princess Margaret Hospital for all the support that it has provided to this,

971
00:58:45.948 --> 00:58:49.788
our collaborators, funders, and most importantly, the patients and

972
00:58:49.888 --> 00:58:52.928
families who have made this possible. Thank you so much.

973
00:58:59.208 --> 00:59:02.468
Thank you very much, Enrique. Do we have any questions?

974
00:59:04.308 --> 00:59:05.868
Maybe I'll start with one.

975
00:59:07.348 --> 00:59:09.968
You highlight some of these cases that were

976
00:59:10.928 --> 00:59:13.668
ctDNA MRD negative, but nonetheless relapsed.

977
00:59:13.698 --> 00:59:14.128
Do you think

978
00:59:15.168 --> 00:59:19.128
is that an opportunity where using one of these genome-wide ultrasensitive

979
00:59:19.228 --> 00:59:23.028
assays with lower limit of detection less than 100 ppm, is that an

980
00:59:23.067 --> 00:59:25.528
opportunity to potentially catch some of those?

981
00:59:26.028 --> 00:59:27.648
Yeah. Thank you so much for that question.

982
00:59:27.988 --> 00:59:30.008
So I think that's one of the reasons mainly.

983
00:59:30.948 --> 00:59:34.548
The assay that we used when we initiated the study was

984
00:59:34.888 --> 00:59:35.928
three years ago. The

985
00:59:38.228 --> 00:59:39.848
technologies have evolved since then.

986
00:59:40.688 --> 00:59:43.748
As I mentioned at the end of my presentation, we are planning to reopen the

987
00:59:43.768 --> 00:59:46.108
MERIDIAN study using a

988
00:59:47.448 --> 00:59:50.457
potential more sensitive assay using whole genome sequencing in the tumor and

989
00:59:50.508 --> 00:59:54.088
tracking up to 1,400 variants, and we are also planning to do some

990
00:59:54.128 --> 00:59:56.488
analysis using other assays of this MERIDIAN cohort.

991
00:59:57.188 --> 01:00:00.908
Another reason, another point I want to highlight is that as you can see, we were

992
01:00:00.928 --> 01:00:04.808
able to detect patients who have a recurrence within a year of the

993
01:00:05.108 --> 01:00:08.928
positive sample. I think it's more difficult to find those who have a recurrence

994
01:00:08.948 --> 01:00:12.888
more than a year, right? And I don't know if those new sensitive assays

995
01:00:12.908 --> 01:00:14.688
are going to be able to catch those patients.

996
01:00:16.108 --> 01:00:16.588
